DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jfi.2014.02.004
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1042957314000138
KW  - Debt
KW  - Equity
KW  - Soft budget constraint
KW  - Monitoring
AB  - We demonstrate an inherent conflict between ex ante efficient monitoring and liquidation decisions by outside claimholders. We show it can be useful to commit to inefficient liquidation when monitors fail to produce information: this provides stronger incentives to monitor. The implication for firm capital structure is that more information is generated about firm prospects – and hence firm value increases – when a firm’s cash flow is split into a ‘safe’ claim (debt) and a ‘risky’ claim (equity) compared to when a single claim is sold. We also derive the optimal allocation of control rights between safe and risky claims. This partially resolves the Tirole (2001) puzzle as to why firms issue multiple securities that generate ex post conflicts of interest.
